\begin_layout Section*
TO MAKE BIRCH WINE
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In March bore a hole in a tree, and put in a faucet, and it will run two
 or three days together without hurting the tree, then put in a pin to stop
 it, and the next year you may draw as much from the same hole; put to every
 gallon of the liquor a quart of good honey, and stir it well together,
 boil it an hour, scum it well and put in a few cloves and a piece of lemon
 peel; when 'tis almost cold put to it so much ale-yeast as will make it
 work like a new ale, and when the yeast begins to settle, put it in a runlet
 that will just hold it; so let it stand six weeks or longer if you please;
 then bottle it and in a month you may drink it.
 It will keep a year or two.
 You may make it with sugar, two pounds to a gallon, or something more,
 if you keep it long.
 This is admirably wholesome, as well as pleasant, an opener of obstructions,
 good against the phthisick, and good against the spleen and scurvey; a
 remedy for the stone, it will abate heat in a fever or thrush, and has
 been given with good success.
\end_layout

